<methodology slug="mob-programming">
  <metadata>
    <tier>free</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>software-developer</domain>
    <summary>Team practice where all work on one task at one machine with rotating Driver, strong-style navigation, strict 5-10 min rotation, written goal. Eliminates delays and knowledge silos.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>mob-programming</tag>
      <tag>pair-programming</tag>
      <tag>teamwork</tag>
      <tag>knowledge-transfer</tag>
      <tag>collaboration</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Mob Programming</title>
    <summary>A team practice where all members work together on one task at one machine: a rotating Driver types only what the Navigator(s) dictate, and ideas must pass through someone else's hands before reaching the keyboard. Strong-style navigation, strict 5-10 minute rotation, and a written session goal are the three load-bearing constraints.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Mobs eliminate review-after-the-fact delays, knowledge silos, and unequal context distribution. Cycle time drops because decisions are made in real-time with full team context. The practice only works when rotation discipline is maintained — without it, drivers fatigue and navigators disengage, collapsing into a lecture with one person coding.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>High-stakes changes requiring multiple specialists simultaneously (payment flow, schema migration, security refactor).</item>
        <item>Onboarding: new engineer navigates while the team drives — knowledge transfers in hours.</item>
        <item>"Impossible" production bugs requiring frontend + backend + ops context simultaneously.</item>
        <item>Killing a knowledge silo when the only expert is leaving.</item>
        <item>Cross-team API contract design where decisions must stick.</item>
        <item>Spreading a new technique (TDD, hexagonal arch) across the team via kata.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Routine CRUD, typo fixes, dependency bumps — overhead exceeds benefit.</item>
        <item>Async teams with more than three time zones — coordination cost exceeds knowledge gain.</item>
        <item>Solo founder or two-person team — that is pairing, not mobbing.</item>
        <item>When more than 50 percent of time is spent waiting on builds or external APIs.</item>
        <item>Teams that have never paired — start with pairing for 2-4 weeks first.</item>
        <item>Tasks the team genuinely needs to parallelize to hit a deadline.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="strong-style-navigation">
      <rule>
        <statement>For an idea to go from your head to the computer, it must go through someone else's hands. The Driver types only what the Navigator dictates; the Driver does not make independent decisions.</statement>
        <rationale>Without this constraint, the most fluent typist dominates and the mob collapses into one person coding with an audience. Strong-style enforces contribution from every navigator.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Navigate at the intent level, not the dictation level. "Create a User class storing name and email" beats "type public class User".</statement>
        <rationale>Dictation-level navigation transfers no knowledge. Intent-level navigation requires the driver to translate understanding into code, cementing learning for everyone.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="rotation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Rotate the driver every 5-10 minutes, enforced by a visible timer. No exceptions during the learning phase.</statement>
        <rationale>Without rotation, driver fatigue sets in and navigators disengage. The mob becomes a lecture with one person coding. Strict rotation builds the muscle; experienced mobs can later switch to natural transitions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="session-goal">
      <rule>
        <statement>Write a single-sentence Done definition before the session starts. Display it visibly throughout. If you cannot write it, do not start the mob.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a written goal, mob sessions drift into exploration and the retrospective becomes "we discussed a lot" — that is procrastination, not collaboration.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="breaks">
      <rule>
        <statement>Take a real break (away from the screen) every 75-90 minutes. Skipping breaks is the primary cause of post-mob burnout and introvert attrition.</statement>
        <rationale>Sustained mob work is cognitively intense. Breaks allow individuals to process, recover, and return engaged. Sessions without breaks degrade in quality after 90 minutes regardless of rotation.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="retrospective">
      <rule>
        <statement>Hold a written retrospective after every session: what worked, what slowed us, one experiment for next time.</statement>
        <rationale>The retrospective is where the mob actually learns to mob. Without it, every session repeats the same friction. In writing because verbal-only retrospectives leave no trace for the next session.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="mob-variants">
      <p>Different mob styles suit different learning goals and problem types. TDD mob: Navigator describes test intent, Driver writes failing test, rotate, new Navigator describes implementation, Driver makes test pass, rotate, refactor together. Benefits: TDD discipline is enforced by the group, tests are clear because the intent is spoken aloud, and design emerges collaboratively. Learning mob: An expert explains concepts while the team drives hands-on. No pressure for output. Rotation is slower (15-20 min). Questions are encouraged. Used to spread a new technique (TDD, hexagonal architecture, a new framework) across the team in one session. Bug-hunt mob: When a critical production bug cannot be solved alone and requires cross-discipline context. Reproduce together, hypothesize causes, test hypotheses systematically, fix collaboratively, add regression test, document root cause. The mob's strength is all relevant context present simultaneously. Randori: One exercise (kata), each person adds one line/change, rotate after each change. Must keep tests green. If stuck, ask for help. Time-boxed at 1-2 hours. Used for learning and spreading patterns through micro-contribution rounds.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="remote-setup">
      <list>
        <item>Video: Zoom or Meet with cameras on.</item>
        <item>Driving: VS Code Live Share or Tuple for low-latency screen share.</item>
        <item>Timer: mobti.me (shared URL visible to all).</item>
        <item>Whiteboard: Miro or FigJam for diagrams.</item>
        <item>Smaller mob for remote (3-4 people); shorter sessions (60-90 min); more frequent breaks.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="disagreement-resolution">
      <rule>
        <statement>Time-box disagreements to 2 minutes, then try one approach and learn from the result. Experiments beat debates because code is cheap to change.</statement>
        <rationale>Endless debate is the most common mob killer after rotation failure. A short time-box forces commitment to action; the retrospective is the right venue for deeper evaluation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Maintain a parking lot for off-topic items. Review at the retrospective. Never derail the session for an item that can wait 90 minutes.</statement>
        <rationale>Off-topic discussions break flow and signal to the team that the session goal is not respected. The parking lot preserves ideas without cost to focus.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="failure-modes">
      <p>Antipatterns that undermine mob cohesion, learning, or output quality. Tourist mob: most participants not engaged, scrolling phones, not following or contributing. The mob's value is proportional to active participation. Disengaged observers get no knowledge transfer and drag the mob's energy down. Use round-robin navigation and active facilitation to prevent this. Expert dominance: one senior person monologues; juniors become typists without understanding. The mob becomes a one-to-many knowledge transfer instead of collaborative construction. The expert's mental model stays with the expert. Enforce strong-style navigation and facilitator-managed turn-taking. No rotation: the driver stays at the keyboard until a task is "done". Driver fatigue causes errors and reduces quality. Other team members disengage without the keyboard. Rotation is the practice's load-bearing constraint — without it, there is no mob. Mobbing everything: all tasks, all day, every day. Mob programming is high-cost, high-value. Applying it to routine CRUD, dependency bumps, or simple refactors wastes the intensity. Reserve it for complex, knowledge-intensive, or high-stakes work. No retrospective after the session. The retrospective is where the mob learns to mob better. Without it, every session repeats the same friction: the same person dominates, breaks get skipped, the goal drifts. Problems persist indefinitely. Mobbing with a two-person team. Two people is pairing, not mobbing. The mob's benefits (cross-discipline context, knowledge distribution, collective decision-making) require at least three participants. Start with the pair-programming methodology.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="limitations-and-costs">
      <p>Throughput illusion: Cycle time can drop, but raw story-point velocity often stays flat or dips. If management measures only velocity, mobbing looks "wasteful" and gets killed. Driver fatigue and cognitive overload: Without strict 5-10 min rotation people zone out; rotation discipline is the load-bearing wall. Dominant voices: One senior engineer monologues; juniors become typists. Without active facilitation the mob becomes a lecture. Remote latency: More than 150ms input lag on Live Share or Tuple breaks the navigator-driver feedback loop. Becomes "watch one person code on a call." Tooling drift: Different IDEs, keymaps, OS shells slow rotation. The mob's productivity equals the slowest setup. No clear DoD: Without a written goal and visible timer, sessions drift; the retro becomes "we explored a lot" — that's procrastination. Burnout: Sustained mobbing more than 4h/day exhausts introverts. Mix with solo blocks or attrition follows.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Mob programming is a human practice — the AI value is in facilitation and capture, not driving. Use a Claude subagent as a silent fifth seat: it watches the screen via shared transcript, takes structured notes, surfaces decisions/ADRs, queues follow-up tasks, and runs the rotation timer. Treat the agent as the scribe + timer + retrospective miner, not the navigator. After the session, a second agent generates the commit message, updates .aidocs/ decision log, and converts parking-lot items into SDD todo/ tasks.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent converts mob-session decisions and parking-lot items into SDD tasks under .aidocs/.../todo/; verifies the mob's WIP commit matches the spec. password-scrubber-agent scrubs the session transcript before publishing the retro; mobs frequently leak credentials, customer names, internal hostnames pasted into the IDE. A purpose-built mob-scribe agent (worth creating): given the live transcript, output decisions.md, parking-lot.md, tests-added.md, and a retro skeleton. nero-sdd-executor-agent — when mobbing on NERO repos, drives the post-session task creation directly into the NERO .product/ lifecycle.</p>
      <p>Scribe pass (run live, every 10 min): Read the diff since the last checkpoint and the last 10 minutes of voice transcript. Output decisions made (one line each, with rationale), parking lot items (off-topic, who raised it), tests added/changed (file + name), and open questions still unresolved. Do NOT suggest code. Do not propose direction. Observe only.</p>
      <p>Post-session pass: Given the session transcript and final diff, produce (1) a 50-char commit title and body explaining the why, (2) SDD task entries for each parking-lot item (path: .aidocs/.../todo/), (3) a 200-word retro draft: what worked, what slowed us, one experiment for next mob, (4) list of new patterns/mistakes to log under .aidocs/memory/.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Goal on the wall: Single-sentence DoD visible at all times. If you cannot write it, do not start the mob.</item>
        <item>Strong-style navigation: "For an idea to go from your head to the computer, it must go through someone else's hands." Eliminates expert hijacking.</item>
        <item>5-10 minute rotation, no exceptions: Even mid-thought. Builds the muscle; once the team trusts handoffs, switch to natural transitions.</item>
        <item>Identical dev env: Standardize keymap, font size, OS shortcuts before the first mob — or pair mismatched people deliberately to surface friction.</item>
        <item>Parking lot is sacred: Off-topic ideas go to the lot, never derail the mob. Review at retro.</item>
        <item>Hard breaks every 75-90 min: Real breaks, away from the screen. Skipping them is the number one cause of post-mob exhaustion.</item>
        <item>Mob the hard half-hour, solo the easy two hours: Do not mob the whole day; pick the high-leverage segment.</item>
        <item>Retro every session, in writing: A mob without a retro is theater; the retro is where the team actually learns.</item>
        <item>Senior pairs with junior on rotation: Always alternate experience levels at the keyboard; otherwise juniors only ever drive.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>The agent is not a navigator: LLMs will happily propose code; in mob mode that overrides human navigators and collapses the practice. Lock the agent to "observe + capture" via system prompt. Transcript hallucination: Speech-to-text mishears jargon ("Kafka" to "kept ya"); the agent will then invent decisions that were never made. Always cite timestamp + speaker in the scribe output, and require human sign-off on the decisions section before commit. Rotation timing drift: If the agent runs the timer, beware of model-call latency causing 30-60s skew. Use a local setInterval / shell timer; the agent only announces. Parking-lot inflation: Agents over-extract every aside as a parking-lot item; the list becomes 40 entries no one revisits. Cap at 10 per session, ranked by how often the topic was raised. Privacy leak: Mob screens contain prod credentials, PII pasted into IDEs, customer names, internal URLs. Run password-scrubber-agent before any external sharing of the transcript, retro, or PR description. Bias toward "everything went great": Agents inherit the meeting's positive close; retros come out anodyne. Force a structured "what slowed us, what was awkward, what should we stop" prompt. No HITL on commits: Never let the agent merge "mob done" to main automatically. The human mob owns the green-light; the agent only drafts the commit message. Remote-only blind spot: Agents miss body language; a confused face is invisible in the transcript. Schedule a brief "any silent confusion?" round-robin every rotation. Onboarding paradox: Agents will cheerfully scribe for a 2-person "mob" — but that's pairing. Refuse to start scribing with less than 3 humans; tell the user to use the pair-programming methodology.</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/mob-session.sh" purpose="Session bootstrapper: creates WIP branch, log file, draft PR, rotation bell."/>
    </templates>
